    "John T. Carroll": "), an activity that proves necessary because, even though God can\nbe trusted to deliver justice speedily, injustice is tenacious and faith is therefore\nvulnerable (vv. 6\u20138).\nThe parable itself is memorable, both in its vivid characterization and in the\nunusual actions its brief plot depicts. A judge who should know better ignores\na widow\u2019s repeated petitions for justice (on the mandate for compassionate\n[v_Deu_24_17] justice in treatment of widows, see, e.g., Deut 24:17; Isa 1:17). Perhaps he does\nknow better; nevertheless, he neither fears (reveres) God117 nor holds anything\nbut contempt for other human beings\u2014such is the parabolic narrator\u2019s (Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`\u2019)\nharsh characterization of him (",
